1362","1373":"1373","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","20 July 1420":"20 July 1420","1412":"1412","1433":"1433","1420":"1420","27 August 1396":"27 August 1396","10 September 1416":"10 September 1416","about 1395":"about 1395","1416":"1416","Snitterfield, Warwickshire, England":"Snitterfield, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Tybeste, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Upsall, Yorkshire, England":"Upsall, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Thorley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly Staffordshire): habitational name, in most cases probably a variant of   Thornley  , although there are places called Thorley (in Hertfordshire and in Lincolnshire), which could have contributed to the surname; these are also named from Old English <i>thorn</i> ‘thorn bush’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, woodland clearing’."],"variants":[{"name":"Thawley","meanings":["English (Warwickshire and Derbyshire): variant of   Thorley  ."]},{"name":"Thornley","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire): habitational name from Thornley in Lancashire, and perhaps also from Thornyleigh near Heaton in Leek (Staffordshire) and Thornleigh in Huddersfield (Yorkshire). The Lancashire name derives from Old English <i>thornede</i> ‘thorny’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, woodland clearing’. The other placenames derive from Old English <i>thorn</i> ‘thorn tree’ or <i>thornig</i> ‘thorny’ + <i>lēah</i>."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":22,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Thorley was born in 1360, in Cornwall, England, his father, Robert Thorley of Bybeste, was 21 and his mother, Dama En Blanco, was 19. He married Anne de la Pole about 1395, in Snitterfield, Warwickshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died on 20 July 1420, in Cornwall, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1360–20 July 1420":"1360–20. juuli 1420","1360–1420":"1360–1420","1373–1412":"1373–1412","1362–1416":"1362–1416","1396–1433":"1396–1433","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1341–Female":"1341–Surnud","30 March 1412":"30. märts 1412","after 30 March 1412":"pärast 30. märtsi 1412","1341":"1341","1396":"1396","1340":"1340","1362":"1362","1373":"1373","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","20 July 1420":"20. juuli 1420","1412":"1412","1433":"1433","1420":"1420","27 August 1396":"27. august 1396","10 September 1416":"10. september 1416","about 1395":"umbes 1395","1416":"1416","Snitterfield, Warwickshire, England":"Snitterfield, Warwicks